---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";
---

<Section id="harmonypir-offline-online" num="06" title="HarmonyPIR — stateful PIR against one server">
  <p>
    <strong>HarmonyPIR</strong> is a single-server <em>stateful</em> PIR
    scheme. There is one honest-but-curious server holding the database,
    and no non-collusion assumption. The scheme's leverage comes from a
    different direction: the client is willing to do work <em>once</em>,
    up front, to make every later query cheap.
  </p>
  <p>
    The protocol splits into two phases. In the <strong>offline</strong>
    phase, the client streams the whole database from the server once and
    condenses it into a short list of <em>hints</em> that it keeps locally.
    In the <strong>online</strong> phase, each query is small in both
    directions — roughly √<code>N</code> entries in the request, √<code>N</code>
    entries in the response — and the client recovers the target row by
    combining the response with one of its hints. After about √<code>N</code>
    queries the hints are used up and the offline phase has to run again.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="One-time streaming pass during offline; short symmetric round-trips for every online query, each reusing the precomputed hint table."
    label="Offline / online split"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 260" role="img"
      aria-label="A single server. Offline phase: the whole database streams down once; client builds hints. Online phase: many short query/response round-trips."
      data-anim="harmony-split">

      <defs>
        <marker id="hs-arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5"
          markerWidth="5" markerHeight="5" orient="auto">
          <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--accent)"/>
        </marker>
        <marker id="hs-arr-ok" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5"
          markerWidth="5" markerHeight="5" orient="auto">
          <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--ok)"/>
        </marker>
      </defs>

      <!-- Offline phase -->
      <g transform="translate(0,10)">
        <text x="16" y="14" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)">OFFLINE — once per epoch</text>
        <rect x="14" y="30" width="100" height="56" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="64" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Client</text>
        <text x="64" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">builds hints</text>
        <text x="64" y="81" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label" fill="var(--accent)">O(N) in</text>

        <rect x="260" y="30" width="120" height="56" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="320" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Server</text>
        <text x="320" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">streams DB</text>

        <g class="bulk">
          <path d="M 255 57 L 119 57" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="3"
            stroke-dasharray="6 3" fill="none" marker-end="url(#hs-arr)"/>
        </g>
        <text x="186" y="105" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label"
          fill="var(--accent)">full database, one pass</text>
      </g>

      <line x1="410" y1="18" x2="410" y2="240" stroke="var(--border)"
        stroke-dasharray="3 4"/>

      <!-- Online phase -->
      <g transform="translate(420,10)">
        <text x="4" y="14" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)">ONLINE — every query</text>
        <rect x="0" y="30" width="96" height="56" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="48" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Client</text>
        <text x="48" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">+ local hints</text>
        <text x="48" y="81" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label" fill="var(--ok)">O(√N)</text>

        <rect x="152" y="30" width="104" height="56" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="204" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Server</text>
        <text x="204" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">same one</text>

        <g class="ping p1">
          <circle r="5" fill="var(--ok)"/>
        </g>
        <g class="ping p2">
          <circle r="5" fill="var(--ok)"/>
        </g>
        <g class="ping p3">
          <circle r="5" fill="var(--ok)"/>
        </g>
        <text x="128" y="105" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label"
          fill="var(--ok)">small, frequent — each hides q</text>
      </g>

      <!-- Budget bar underneath -->
      <text x="20" y="150" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        Online queries per offline phase
      </text>
      <g transform="translate(20,160)">
        <rect width="640" height="14" rx="2" fill="var(--bg-elev-2)" stroke="var(--border)"/>
        <rect class="budget" width="0" height="14" rx="2" fill="var(--ok)" opacity="0.8"/>
      </g>
      <text x="20" y="192" font-size="9" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)" font-style="italic">
        After ~N/T queries, all the empty cells in the hint table are used up.
        Rerun offline with a fresh permutation and stream the database again.
      </text>
      <text x="20" y="222" font-size="10" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)">
        The next page unpacks what the hint table actually looks like, and how
        one online query extracts a single row out of a √N-wide batch.
      </text>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <p>
    One subtlety worth flagging up front: the online-phase request is
    <em>not</em> an encrypted version of the query index <code>q</code>.
    It's a batch of √<code>N</code> plain database indices — a slice of the
    client's private hint table — with one of them swapped for a freshly
    sampled random index so the server can't pick out which slot the client
    actually cares about. The server just looks up those indices and sends
    back their values. All of the privacy comes from how the client
    <em>chose</em> the batch, not from any cryptography on the wire. The
    rest of this section is about that choice.
  </p>
</Section>

<style>
  [data-anim="harmony-split"] .bulk { opacity: 0; }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"] .ping { opacity: 0; }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"] .budget { opacity: 0.85; }

  [data-anim="harmony-split"].play .bulk {
    animation: hs-bulkin 1.4s var(--ease) 0.3s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"].play .p1 {
    animation: hs-ping 1.2s var(--ease) 1.8s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"].play .p2 {
    animation: hs-ping 1.2s var(--ease) 2.4s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"].play .p3 {
    animation: hs-ping 1.2s var(--ease) 3.0s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-split"].play .budget {
    animation: hs-budget 3.5s var(--ease) 1.8s forwards;
  }

  @keyframes hs-bulkin {
    0%   { opacity: 0; }
    40%  { opacity: 1; }
    100% { opacity: 0.7; }
  }
  @keyframes hs-ping {
    0%   { opacity: 0; transform: translate(48px, 57px); }
    30%  { opacity: 1; }
    50%  { transform: translate(204px, 57px); }
    70%  { opacity: 1; }
    100% { opacity: 0; transform: translate(48px, 57px); }
  }
  @keyframes hs-budget { to { width: 640px; } }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    [data-anim="harmony-split"] .bulk,
    [data-anim="harmony-split"] .ping { opacity: 0.7 !important; }
    [data-anim="harmony-split"] .budget { width: 640px !important; }
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  document.querySelectorAll('[data-anim="harmony-split"]').forEach((svg) => {
    const stage = svg.closest("[data-stage]");
    const run = () => {
      svg.classList.remove("play");
      void svg.getBoundingClientRect();
      svg.classList.add("play");
    };
    stage?.addEventListener("stage:visible", run);
    svg.addEventListener("click", run);
  });
</script>
